<section xml:id="creating-test-cases" version="5.0" xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"
                                                xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude"
                                                xmlns:xl="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" >
  <title>Creating Test Cases</title>
  <anchor role="helpid" condition="testcaseNewContextId" xml:id="creating-test-cases.testcaseNewContextId">New Test Case Dialog</anchor>
  <anchor role="helpid" condition="guidancerSpecTestCaseEditorContextId" xml:id="creating-test-cases.guidancerSpecTestCaseEditorContextId">Test Case Editor</anchor>
  <anchor role="helpid" condition="testSpecificationViewContextId" xml:id="creating-test-cases.testSpecificationViewContextId">Test Case Browser</anchor>
  <para>
    Most of the time spent writing tests will involve creating and
    editing Test Cases.
  </para>
  <para>
    To create a Test Case, you must have created or opened a Project
    (<xref linkend="working-with-projects"/>).
  </para>
  <para>
    The Test Case Browser must also be visible. If it is not visible, change to the Specification Perspective perspective and select:
  </para>
  
  <para>
    <emphasis role="menuPath">Window</emphasis>--&gt;<emphasis role="menuPath">Show View</emphasis>--&gt;<emphasis role="menuPath">Test Case Browser</emphasis>.
  </para>
  <para role="tip">
    You can also have multiple instances of the Test Case
    Browser open (<xref linkend="opening-the-test-case-browser-multiple-times"/>).
  </para>
  <orderedlist>
    <listitem>
      <para>
        Create a Test Case by using the context-sensitive menu in the Test Case Browser:
      </para>
        
      <para>
        <emphasis role="menuPath">New</emphasis>--&gt;<emphasis role="menuPath">New Test Case</emphasis>.
      </para>
      
      <para role="tip">
        You can also create Test Cases with a double-click on the ”<emphasis>Test Cases:</emphasis>” root entry or on a category in the Test Case Browser.
      </para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para>
        A dialog to name the Test Case will appear
        (<xref linkend="newtestcasedialog"/>). Because the testing approach
        is keyword-driven, it is important to name Test Cases
        meaningfully – you will be able to read your tests easily
        and quickly choose which Test Case you need.
      </para>
      <figure xml:id="newtestcasedialog">
        <title>New Test Case Dialog</title>
        <mediaobject>
          <imageobject>
            <imagedata fileref="images/newtestcasedialog.png"/>
          </imageobject>
          <textobject><phrase>New Test Case
          Dialog</phrase></textobject>
        </mediaobject>
      </figure>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para>
        Click ”<emphasis>OK</emphasis>”.
      </para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para>
        This creates a new Test Case with that name in the Test Case
        Browser (<xref linkend="newtestcaseinbrowser"/>).
      </para>
      <figure xml:id="newtestcaseinbrowser">
        <title>Test Case in Test Case Browser</title>
        <mediaobject>
          <imageobject>
            <imagedata fileref="images/newtestcaseinbrowser.png"/>
          </imageobject>
          <textobject><phrase>Test Case in Test Case
          Browser</phrase></textobject>
        </mediaobject>
      </figure>
    </listitem>
  </orderedlist>
  <para><emphasis role="strong">Next steps</emphasis><?linebreak?>
    The next step is to add Test Cases from the library of Test Cases to this Test Case (<xref linkend="creating-tests-from-the-library-of-pre-defined-test-cases"/>).
  </para>
  <para>
    You can also:
  </para>
  <itemizedlist>
    <listitem>
      <para>
        Reuse this Test Case to form other Test Cases
        (<xref linkend="adding-items-to-editors"/>)
      </para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para>
        Edit its content in the Test Case Editor
        (<xref linkend="working-with-editors"/>)
      </para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para>
        Add this Test Case to a Test Suite to be executed
        (<xref linkend="adding-items-to-editors"/>)
      </para>
    </listitem>
    <listitem>
      <para>
        Use this Test Case as an Event Handler
        (<xref linkend="dealing-with-errors-in-tests"/>).
      </para>
    </listitem>
  </itemizedlist>
</section>